<B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Ind</FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=5>ices(Powers) Learning Plan 2</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">Negative &amp; Fractional Powers</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial">
<P>While working through this plan you may find it helpful to refer to the lecture notes titled ‘Review of Indices’.</P>

<B><P>Negative Powers</P>

</B><P>It is possible for powers to take negative values.   Consider the expression below.   Applying the Division rule gives</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">a<SUP>3</SUP>/a<SUP>5</SUP> = a<SUP>3-5</SUP> = a<B><SUP>-2</P>
</SUP><P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
</B><P>Expanding the calculation</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">a<SUP>3</SUP>/a<SUP>5</SUP> = (axaxa)/(axaxaxaxa) = 1/a<SUP>2</P>
</SUP><P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>hence </P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">a<B><SUP>-2</SUP> </B>=<B> </B>1/a<SUP>2</P>
</SUP>
<P>Work in more detail with negative powers in <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 a~?">1-24 section a</a>  and  <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 b~?">section b</a>.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Fractional Powers</P>

</B><P>Powers can also take fractional values.   Find the meaning of 2<SUP>1/2</SUP> in <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 c~?">1-24 section c</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 d~?">section d</a>.   Spend time working with fractional indices in <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 e~?">section e</a>, <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 f~?">section f</a> and 
<a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 g 1~?">section g tutorial 1, <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 g 2~?">tutorial 2</a> and <a href="runcal.htm#==k:\calmat\tcrun.exe calpopup //?~ 0 1 24 g 3~?">tutorial 3</a>.</P>

<P>Try <a href="launch.htm#q0206">q0206</a>.</P></FONT></BODY>
